1
00:00:01,669 --> 00:00:01,899
.

2
00:00:01,902 --> 00:00:04,072
<i>- Previously on "Suits"...
- I don't owe Harvey shit.</i>

3
00:00:04,073 --> 00:00:05,401
He may have gotten me out,

4
00:00:05,406 --> 00:00:06,506
but he done came and put me
in there in the first place.

5
00:00:06,507 --> 00:00:07,737
- You're right,
you don't owe Harvey,

6
00:00:07,742 --> 00:00:09,110
but you do owe me
because I didn't have anything

7
00:00:09,111 --> 00:00:10,280
to do with putting you in there,

8
00:00:10,281 --> 00:00:12,777
but I broke the law
to get you out.

9
00:00:12,780 --> 00:00:15,580
- I came here to compliment you
on getting rid of Sheila's ass.

10
00:00:15,583 --> 00:00:17,953
If she's not back
by the start of trial,

11
00:00:17,954 --> 00:00:20,352
I'm gonna assume you want
to be brought up on charges.

12
00:00:20,354 --> 00:00:22,254
- I just stopped by to give you
this restraining order

13
00:00:22,256 --> 00:00:24,316
preventing you
from contacting Louis Litt.

14
00:00:24,325 --> 00:00:26,625
You're done driving a wedge
between me and my people.

15
00:00:26,627 --> 00:00:28,887
- If I represent myself,
every second I'm up there

16
00:00:28,896 --> 00:00:30,196
they're gonna see me
as a lawyer.

17
00:00:30,197 --> 00:00:31,357
- And if she rattles you

18
00:00:31,365 --> 00:00:32,995
for one of those
goddamn seconds,

19
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:34,367
they're gonna see you as a fraud

20
00:00:34,368 --> 00:00:36,268
and they're never gonna see you
as anything else.

21
00:00:36,270 --> 00:00:40,170
- Did Mike Ross go
to Harvard Law School or not?

22
00:00:40,174 --> 00:00:43,212
- I'd like to assert
my Fifth Amendment right.

23
00:00:43,213 --> 00:00:45,378
- If I was on that jury,
I'd find you guilty.

24
00:00:45,379 --> 00:00:47,149
- They're not gonna
let me change my goddamn lawyer

25
00:00:47,150 --> 00:00:48,548
in the middle of a trial.

26
00:00:48,549 --> 00:00:50,019
- We need to figure out
a way to make them,

27
00:00:50,020 --> 00:00:52,017
'cause if we don't,
we're gonna lose.

28
00:00:52,019 --> 00:00:54,649
- You have one last chance
to save yourself.

29
00:00:54,655 --> 00:00:57,555
Call me before it's too late.

30
00:01:01,095 --> 00:01:03,155
- Okay, so we have
a plan for you

31
00:01:03,164 --> 00:01:04,533
to start representing yourself.

32
00:01:04,534 --> 00:01:07,102
We just need a way to rattle
Gibbs when we execute it.

33
00:01:07,103 --> 00:01:08,868
- I have a way, but...

34
00:01:08,869 --> 00:01:12,138
you're not gonna like it.

35
00:01:12,139 --> 00:01:13,809
I'm gonna call Clifford Danner
to the stand.

36
00:01:13,810 --> 00:01:15,268
- No way, it's too risky.

37
00:01:15,276 --> 00:01:17,606
- Harvey, listen to me...
- He's angry and volatile

38
00:01:17,611 --> 00:01:18,841
and in case you forgot,

39
00:01:18,846 --> 00:01:20,346
he's one of the people
you were dumb enough

40
00:01:20,347 --> 00:01:22,247
to tell your secret to.
- I know all of that,

41
00:01:22,249 --> 00:01:24,419
but you said it yourself,
we need sympathy,

42
00:01:24,420 --> 00:01:26,188
and no one is gonna
get us more sympathy

43
00:01:26,189 --> 00:01:28,387
than the innocent guy
we got out of prison.

44
00:01:28,389 --> 00:01:30,589
Harvey, you said
I needed to do this.

45
00:01:30,591 --> 00:01:32,959
Well, this is how I do it.

46
00:01:32,960 --> 00:01:34,560
<i>[tense music]</i>

47
00:01:34,562 --> 00:01:36,729
Do you have faith in me or not?

48
00:01:36,730 --> 00:01:43,636
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49
00:01:43,637 --> 00:01:44,797
[door opens]

50
00:01:46,040 --> 00:01:47,570
Mrs. Gloria Danner?

51
00:01:47,575 --> 00:01:49,875
- Yes.
- Hi, my name is Mike Ross.

52
00:01:49,877 --> 00:01:52,107
I'm a lawyer at Pearson Specter
Litt and I was hoping...

53
00:01:52,113 --> 00:01:53,580
- I know who you are,

54
00:01:53,581 --> 00:01:55,751
and I know
what you're doing here.

55
00:01:55,752 --> 00:01:59,179
You've come to get Clifford
to testify for you,

56
00:01:59,186 --> 00:02:01,186
but I'm afraid
he's not going to.

57
00:02:01,188 --> 00:02:03,888
- Please, ma'am, I promise you,
the DA cannot reopen his case...

58
00:02:03,891 --> 00:02:07,391
- I'm not talking
about the district attorney.

59
00:02:07,394 --> 00:02:10,363
My son's dead, Mr. Ross.

60
00:02:10,364 --> 00:02:12,031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

61
00:02:12,032 --> 00:02:14,102
- What?
- Clifford was shot and killed

62
00:02:14,103 --> 00:02:16,901
three weeks ago, so...

63
00:02:16,904 --> 00:02:19,304
I'm sorry, he can't help you.

64
00:02:19,306 --> 00:02:21,506
<i>♪ ♪</i>

65
00:02:21,509 --> 00:02:23,109
<i>- Hello?</i>
- Are you in the office?

66
00:02:23,110 --> 00:02:25,110
<i>- It's Thursday night.
I'm watching my show.</i>

67
00:02:25,112 --> 00:02:27,382
<i>- Well, then goddamn Tivo it
because I need your help.</i>

68
00:02:27,383 --> 00:02:30,081
- It better be important if
you're taking that tone with me.

69
00:02:30,084 --> 00:02:32,118
And if this is
about that mah-jongg game...

70
00:02:32,119 --> 00:02:33,519
- I don't give a shit
if it's mah-jongg

71
00:02:33,521 --> 00:02:35,451
or kung pao or Chinese checkers.

72
00:02:35,456 --> 00:02:36,886
This is the most important thing

73
00:02:36,891 --> 00:02:39,321
that I'm ever gonna ask you
to do in your entire life.

74
00:02:39,326 --> 00:02:41,326
- Give me an order.

75
00:02:41,328 --> 00:02:42,996
<i>- I need you to pull
whatever strings you have</i>

76
00:02:42,997 --> 00:02:44,557
to get me a transcript
of Mike's trial

77
00:02:44,565 --> 00:02:46,095
and I need you
to keep it to yourself.

78
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:47,600
- Mind if I ask
what you need it for?

79
00:02:47,601 --> 00:02:49,941
- Because I need to know if we
have a snowball's chance in hell

80
00:02:49,942 --> 00:02:51,667
of winning this thing.

81
00:02:51,672 --> 00:02:54,372
- Is defense ready
to call its first witness?

82
00:02:54,375 --> 00:02:56,175
- I am, Your Honor.
- What?

83
00:02:56,177 --> 00:02:57,337
- I'm calling my witness.

84
00:02:57,344 --> 00:02:59,614
Does prosecution have a problem
with that?

85
00:02:59,615 --> 00:03:01,713
- Objection, this is outrageous,
Your Honor.

86
00:03:01,715 --> 00:03:03,615
They can't switch attorneys
in the middle of a trial.

87
00:03:03,617 --> 00:03:05,247
- And that would be true
except for the fact

88
00:03:05,252 --> 00:03:07,422
that I've been co-counsel
on this case from day one.

89
00:03:07,423 --> 00:03:09,251
- Co-counsel?
What planer are you living on?

90
00:03:09,256 --> 00:03:11,856
- The one where Pearson Specter
Litt is my attorney of record.

91
00:03:11,859 --> 00:03:13,689
I have the employee directory
right here.

92
00:03:13,694 --> 00:03:15,032
My name is in it.
It's been there

93
00:03:15,033 --> 00:03:16,359
since the beginning
of this trial,

94
00:03:16,363 --> 00:03:17,631
and if you wanted
to object to me,

95
00:03:17,632 --> 00:03:18,801
you would have had
to have done it

96
00:03:18,802 --> 00:03:20,299
at the beginning of this trial.

97
00:03:20,301 --> 00:03:22,069
- Then I want them waiving
all rights to a mistrial

98
00:03:22,070 --> 00:03:23,537
and I want it in the record.
- Your Honor,

99
00:03:23,538 --> 00:03:25,367
I'm not gonna be punished just
because she didn't understand

100
00:03:25,372 --> 00:03:27,672
that I've been representing
myself this whole time.

101
00:03:27,675 --> 00:03:28,905
- He's got a point, Ms. Gibbs.

102
00:03:28,909 --> 00:03:31,039
- Then I want them waiving
all rights to a mistrial

103
00:03:31,045 --> 00:03:32,905
based on
him representing himself.

104
00:03:32,913 --> 00:03:34,383
- My pleasure, Your Honor,
'cause I don't expect

105
00:03:34,384 --> 00:03:36,011
we'll be needing a mistrial
at all.

106
00:03:36,016 --> 00:03:37,446
- Then call your first witness.

107
00:03:37,451 --> 00:03:41,221
- Defense would like to call
Gloria Danner to the stand.

108
00:03:41,222 --> 00:03:42,892
<i>Please state your name
for the jury.</i>

109
00:03:42,893 --> 00:03:45,020
- Gloria Danner.

110
00:03:45,025 --> 00:03:46,885
- Mrs. Danner,

111
00:03:46,894 --> 00:03:48,732
a number of years ago,
your son Clifford

112
00:03:48,733 --> 00:03:51,359
was convicted of murder
and sentenced to prison,

113
00:03:51,365 --> 00:03:53,225
is that right?
- Yes.

114
00:03:53,234 --> 00:03:54,867
For a crime he didn't commit.

115
00:03:54,868 --> 00:03:56,238
- How do you know
he didn't commit it

116
00:03:56,239 --> 00:03:57,497
if he was convicted of it?

117
00:03:57,504 --> 00:03:59,606
- Because you proved he didn't.

118
00:03:59,607 --> 00:04:01,267
- Mrs. Danner,
can you tell the jury

119
00:04:01,275 --> 00:04:03,405
why it is that you're here today
testifying

120
00:04:03,410 --> 00:04:04,940
and not your son Clifford?

121
00:04:04,945 --> 00:04:06,945
- He was working late
at the diner.

122
00:04:06,947 --> 00:04:10,617
It was the only place he could
get a job when he got out.

123
00:04:10,618 --> 00:04:13,118
Two men came in
to rob the place,

124
00:04:13,120 --> 00:04:15,190
and when Clifford tried
to stop them,

125
00:04:15,191 --> 00:04:18,458
he was shot and killed.

126
00:04:18,459 --> 00:04:21,227
<i>[somber music]</i>

127
00:04:21,228 --> 00:04:23,428
- I'm so sorry.

128
00:04:23,430 --> 00:04:27,967
- [crying]
I worked my whole life

129
00:04:27,968 --> 00:04:29,736
to put him through school

130
00:04:29,737 --> 00:04:32,267
and he ends up dying

131
00:04:32,273 --> 00:04:35,173
in the back of that
shit restaurant

132
00:04:35,175 --> 00:04:37,975
in that shit part of town.

133
00:04:37,978 --> 00:04:39,948
- Can you tell the jury
why you agreed

134
00:04:39,949 --> 00:04:42,477
to come share your story
for me today?

135
00:04:42,483 --> 00:04:44,283
<i>♪ ♪</i>

136
00:04:44,285 --> 00:04:46,115
- Prison

137
00:04:46,120 --> 00:04:48,820
ruined Clifford's life...

138
00:04:48,822 --> 00:04:50,222
<i>♪ ♪</i>

139
00:04:50,224 --> 00:04:52,724
And if you had been our lawyer

140
00:04:52,726 --> 00:04:54,586
from day one,

141
00:04:54,595 --> 00:04:57,795
he never would have been
convicted in the first place.

142
00:04:57,798 --> 00:05:01,198
<i>♪ ♪</i>

143
00:05:01,201 --> 00:05:03,036
- Thank you, Gloria.

144
00:05:03,037 --> 00:05:05,237
<i>♪ ♪</i>

145
00:05:05,239 --> 00:05:07,807
No more questions, Your Honor.

146
00:05:07,808 --> 00:05:13,078
<i>♪ ♪</i>

147
00:05:13,080 --> 00:05:14,880
- Mrs. Danner,

148
00:05:14,882 --> 00:05:18,851
I happen to be familiar
with your son's case.

149
00:05:18,852 --> 00:05:21,352
And I understand
that in order to reopen it,

150
00:05:21,355 --> 00:05:25,215
Mr. Ross risked
increasing his sentence to life.

151
00:05:25,225 --> 00:05:26,455
- That's correct.

152
00:05:26,460 --> 00:05:28,330
- Well, I'd like to know
how you'd have felt

153
00:05:28,331 --> 00:05:29,759
if he lost that gamble.

154
00:05:29,763 --> 00:05:31,201
- I'd have been devastated.

155
00:05:31,202 --> 00:05:33,268
- And if that happened,
how would you have felt

156
00:05:33,269 --> 00:05:34,527
if you then found out that

157
00:05:34,535 --> 00:05:37,495
Mr. Ross wasn't even a lawyer
after all?

158
00:05:37,504 --> 00:05:39,974
- Objection, Your Honor, how
many hypotheticals can she ask?

159
00:05:39,975 --> 00:05:41,173
- That's okay.

160
00:05:41,175 --> 00:05:44,035
I think everybody
in this courtroom knows

161
00:05:44,044 --> 00:05:47,213
how they would feel.

162
00:05:47,214 --> 00:05:50,183
No more questions, Your Honor.

163
00:05:50,184 --> 00:05:53,724
- I wouldn't have cared what
a piece of paper had to say,

164
00:05:53,725 --> 00:05:57,690
because Mr. Ross is
the only lawyer I ever ran into

165
00:05:57,691 --> 00:06:00,526
that ever gave a damn
about my son.

166
00:06:00,527 --> 00:06:04,097
<i>♪ ♪</i>

167
00:06:04,098 --> 00:06:07,268
- Mr. Ross, would you care
to call your next witness?

168
00:06:07,269 --> 00:06:11,137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

169
00:06:11,138 --> 00:06:12,298
- I can't imagine anyone

170
00:06:12,306 --> 00:06:14,466
being more eloquent than that,
Your Honor.

171
00:06:14,475 --> 00:06:15,965
<i>♪ ♪</i>

172
00:06:15,976 --> 00:06:19,946
Defense rests.

173
00:06:19,947 --> 00:06:23,647
<i>- ♪ See the money,
wanna stay for your meal ♪</i>

174
00:06:23,650 --> 00:06:26,986
<i>♪ Get another piece of pie
for your wife ♪</i>

175
00:06:26,987 --> 00:06:30,156
<i>♪ Everybody wanna know
how it feel ♪</i>

176
00:06:30,157 --> 00:06:33,926
<i>♪ Everybody wanna see
what it's like ♪</i>

177
00:06:33,927 --> 00:06:36,827
<i>♪ I'll even eat a bean pie,
I don't mind ♪</i>

178
00:06:36,830 --> 00:06:40,830
<i>♪ Me and Missy is
so busy, busy making money ♪</i>

179
00:06:40,834 --> 00:06:42,301
<i>♪ All right ♪</i>

180
00:06:42,302 --> 00:06:47,840
<i>♪ All step back,
I'm 'bout to dance ♪</i>

181
00:06:47,841 --> 00:06:49,011
<i>♪ The greenback boogie ♪</i>

182
00:06:56,316 --> 00:06:56,546
.

183
00:06:56,550 --> 00:06:57,820
- [sighs]
- Having trouble

184
00:06:57,821 --> 00:07:00,486
with your closing?

185
00:07:00,487 --> 00:07:03,287
- No, it's just
part of the process.

186
00:07:03,290 --> 00:07:05,790
- Would it make you feel better
if I told you

187
00:07:05,793 --> 00:07:09,829
that I have never felt more
proud of my future husband

188
00:07:09,830 --> 00:07:12,230
than I did watching you
up there today?

189
00:07:12,232 --> 00:07:15,868
- Yes, it would.

190
00:07:15,869 --> 00:07:17,769
- Good.

191
00:07:17,771 --> 00:07:19,571
Because I want to talk to you
about your closing.

192
00:07:19,573 --> 00:07:21,140
- Ugh.

193
00:07:21,141 --> 00:07:23,341
Don't tell me you want me
to go with jury nullification.

194
00:07:23,343 --> 00:07:25,043
- There is nothing wrong
with getting a jury

195
00:07:25,045 --> 00:07:27,045
to sympathize with you,
and, Mike, your parents died

196
00:07:27,047 --> 00:07:28,347
in a car accident.

197
00:07:28,348 --> 00:07:30,148
Who isn't gonna feel
for a person like that?

198
00:07:30,150 --> 00:07:31,680
- Rachel, the only problem
with me saying,

199
00:07:31,685 --> 00:07:34,385
"Let me off because
tragedy struck me as a child"

200
00:07:34,388 --> 00:07:36,788
is I've pretty much admitted
that I'm guilty.

201
00:07:36,790 --> 00:07:39,160
- No, the difference is that
that accident is the reason

202
00:07:39,161 --> 00:07:41,489
that you wanted to become
a lawyer in the first place.

203
00:07:41,495 --> 00:07:44,655
And they won't just understand
it, they will love you for it.

204
00:07:44,665 --> 00:07:47,795
- How can you know that?

205
00:07:47,801 --> 00:07:51,301
- Because I love you for it.

206
00:07:51,305 --> 00:07:54,665
Tell them your story
and I am telling you,

207
00:07:54,675 --> 00:07:56,675
they'll let you go.

208
00:07:56,677 --> 00:07:59,677
<i>[soft music]</i>

209
00:07:59,680 --> 00:08:02,348
<i>♪ ♪</i>

210
00:08:02,349 --> 00:08:03,949
- Louis, you wanted to see me?

211
00:08:03,951 --> 00:08:05,120
- Yeah, that was hours ago.

212
00:08:05,121 --> 00:08:06,948
We need to talk.
We need to talk right now.

213
00:08:06,954 --> 00:08:08,322
- About what?
- About the fact that

214
00:08:08,323 --> 00:08:10,360
Mike Ross is all of a sudden
representing himself.

215
00:08:10,361 --> 00:08:12,087
- And why exactly do we need
to talk about that?

216
00:08:12,092 --> 00:08:14,592
- Because it means Harvey thinks
he's gonna lose.

217
00:08:14,595 --> 00:08:17,755
- You wanna walk me
through that logic?

218
00:08:17,764 --> 00:08:20,233
- Harvey's never given up
control of a case in his life,

219
00:08:20,234 --> 00:08:21,501
and if he's doing that now,

220
00:08:21,502 --> 00:08:23,102
it means he wants that loss
on Mike's record.

221
00:08:23,103 --> 00:08:24,272
- Louis, at a time like this,

222
00:08:24,273 --> 00:08:26,241
Harvey doesn't care
about records.

223
00:08:26,242 --> 00:08:27,740
- Bullshit.
I read the transcript

224
00:08:27,741 --> 00:08:30,041
backwards and forwards.
He thinks he's gonna lose.

225
00:08:30,043 --> 00:08:31,513
- Louis, what's really
going on here?

226
00:08:31,514 --> 00:08:32,979
- I'll tell you what's going on.

227
00:08:32,980 --> 00:08:34,180
If Harvey thinks
we're gonna lose,

228
00:08:34,181 --> 00:08:35,811
then we'll lose,
and if that happens,

229
00:08:35,816 --> 00:08:38,576
you know who Gibbs
is coming after next.

230
00:08:38,585 --> 00:08:42,545
- Louis, we will deal with that
when and if she does,

231
00:08:42,556 --> 00:08:44,156
but I am telling you,

232
00:08:44,157 --> 00:08:48,127
Harvey letting Mike take
the reins is not him giving up.

233
00:08:48,128 --> 00:08:50,158
It's him growing up

234
00:08:50,163 --> 00:08:53,273
and realizing he is not
the one to bring this home.

235
00:08:53,274 --> 00:09:01,274
<i>♪ ♪</i>

236
00:09:09,149 --> 00:09:11,019
- Do you want to talk about it?

237
00:09:11,020 --> 00:09:13,078
- Talk about what?

238
00:09:13,086 --> 00:09:14,446
- Oh, I don't know,
maybe the fact

239
00:09:14,454 --> 00:09:16,524
that Mike is working
on a closing

240
00:09:16,525 --> 00:09:18,023
to keep himself out of jail

241
00:09:18,025 --> 00:09:20,285
and you're not working on it
with him.

242
00:09:20,294 --> 00:09:22,929
- There's nothing for me to do,
Donna.

243
00:09:22,930 --> 00:09:24,430
It's in his hands.

244
00:09:24,431 --> 00:09:26,131
- In his hands?

245
00:09:26,133 --> 00:09:27,667
Harvey,
that was a trial maneuver.

246
00:09:27,668 --> 00:09:29,468
It doesn't mean you can't
